  "text": "The canonical patterns for deploying services in Kubernetes are distributed across three key repositories:\n\n## API Type Definition\nThe authoritative Deployment struct is defined in github.com/sg-evals/api--v0.32.0 at apps/v1/types.go (lines 358-373). This is the v1 API version, which is the stable, production-ready version. The Deployment type composes metav1.TypeMeta, metav1.ObjectMeta for standard Kubernetes object metadata, and includes a DeploymentSpec (lines 375-418) that specifies the desired behavior including replicas, pod selector, pod template, deployment strategy, and progress deadline settings. The API repo's README.md documents that this is the canonical location of Kubernetes API definitions and should be used as a dependency through client-go.\n\n## Client-Side Code Pattern\nThe canonical Go code example showing how to create a Deployment using the client library is in github.com/sg-evals/client-go--v0.32.0 in examples/create-update-delete-deployment/main.go (lines 65-99). The example demonstrates the standard pattern: (1) Initialize a Kubernetes client using clientcmd.BuildConfigFromFlags, (2) Create a clientset via kubernetes.NewForConfig, (3) Get a typed Deployments client via clientset.AppsV1().Deployments(namespace), (4) Construct a *appsv1.Deployment struct with ObjectMeta (name) and Spec (replicas, selector, template with containers), and (5) Call deploymentsClient.Create(context.TODO(), deployment, metav1.CreateOptions{}). The example continues with update (using retry.RetryOnConflict to handle conflicts), list, and delete operations. The typed client interface is formally defined in kubernetes/typed/apps/v1/deployment.go and includes Create, Update, UpdateStatus, Delete, Get, List, Watch, and Patch methods.\n\n## Developer Documentation\nThe deployment workflow documentation is located in github.com/sg-evals/client-go--v0.32.0 at examples/create-update-delete-deployment/README.md. This README explains the four fundamental operations: (1) Create a 2-replica Deployment with a selector matching pod labels, (2) Update the Deployment by modifying the replica count and container image using the retry pattern to handle conflicts, (3) List Deployments in a namespace, and (4) Delete the Deployment with foreground propagation policy. The examples/README.md provides an overview listing this example under the 'Basics' section as the entry point for managing resources with the Kubernetes API.\n\nThe retry pattern shown in the example (using retry.RetryOnConflict) is the recommended approach for updates, as it preserves changes made by other clients between Create and Update operations by fetching the latest version before modifying."
}

